[2
Date: 29 Mar 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: News International (Pakistan), 29 Mar 2001 [edited
<http://www.jang.com.pk/thenews/index.html>

GUWAHATI, India: Officials said 25 per cent of cattle in India's
northeastern Assam state are infected with foot and mouth disease (FMD) but
there is no cause for panic.
Government veterinarian Kushal Konwar Sharma said the disease was a "common
phenomenon in Assam" and had been detected in most of the 1500 cattle
brought to a routine vaccination camp last week. "There is no cause for
panic. It can be easily controlled," Sharma said. "25 per cent of the
estimated 7.5 million cattle in Assam are afflicted with FMD and steps have
been taken to prevent further spread," he added.
India's desert state of Rajasthan has launched a vaccination drive to
prevent the spread of FMD after some cases of the devastating livestock
illness were reported in the province in the winter season.
